entry.title: Tropical Storm Warning issued November 12 at 5:03PM ChST by NWS Tiyan GU
entry.summary:
...TROPICAL STORM MAN-YI CONTINUES ITS APPROACH...
.NEW INFORMATION... None.
.AREAS AFFECTED... This local statement provides important information and recommended actions for people in Guam and the Northern Marianas.
.Watches/Warnings... A Tropical storm warning continues for Guam and Rota.
A Tropical storm watch continues for Tinian and Saipan.
A Flood Watch is in effect for portions of Guam and the Northern Marianas. Please listen closely for any flood warnings that might be in effect for your area.
Please check the latest public and marine forecasts for detailed information about additional hazards.
.STORM INFORMATION... At 4 PM ChST...the center of Tropical Storm Man-yi (25W) was located near latitude 14.1N...longitude 148.7E. This was about 260 miles east of Guam. Storm motion was west, 265 degrees, at 18 mph. Storm intensity was 45 mph.
.SITUATION OVERVIEW... Tropical Storm Man-yi is poorly organized with the convection displaced south from it's center, due to dry air entrainment into the western and southwestern side of the storm, with wind shear of 20 knots also a factor. However, a gradual strengthening and organization process is expected to occur in the next 12 hours.
.PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...
entry.cap:areaDesc: Rota

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued November 11 at 7:28PM MST by NWS Great Falls MT
entry.summary:
An area of rain and snow will develop across Southwest Montana overnight, initially near the I-15 corridor around midnight, shifting east into Gallatin and Madison counties late tonight through Tuesday morning.
A period of moderate wet snowfall may impact the morning commute in the Bozeman area between 5 AM and 8 AM, particularly for those traveling east over Bozeman pass or south towards Big Sky. Reduced visibility and brief accumulation of slush on road surfaces are the main concern in these areas.
Total snow accumulations of 2 to 4 inches are expected in the mountains of Gallatin, Madison and Beaverhead counties, with 1 to 2 inches over mountain passes and one inch or less at lower elevations, including Dillon, Ennis and Bozeman.
